<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="261" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[140,789,826,1010]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
<emphasis box="[177,672,826,850]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
Distribution and ecology. – 
<taxonomicName box="[449,672,827,850]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Benstonea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="serpentinica">Benstonea serpentinica</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is endemic from Mt. Silam on ultramafic soil in the eastern region of Sabah (
<figureCitation box="[223,287,890,914]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[140,167,1084,1103]" captionTargetBox="[159,787,297,980]" captionTargetId="figure-721@2.[157,789,294,982]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. – Distribution of Benstonea fortuita Callm. &amp; Buerki (white star) and B. serpentinica Callm. &amp; Buerki (white circle) in Borneo. Abbreviations: 1. Crocker Range National Park; 2. Kinabalu Park." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5721718" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5721718/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). This mountain, which culminates at 884 m, is home to several endemic species including the recently described 
<taxonomicName authority="Utteridge, Julius &amp; Suzana" authorityName="Utteridge, Julius &amp; Suzana" box="[260,789,954,978]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Ardisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="silamensis">
<emphasis box="[260,460,954,978]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">Ardisia silamensis</emphasis>
Utteridge, Julius &amp; Suzana
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="UTTERIDGE" box="[148,403,986,1010]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="UTTERIDGE" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" pagination="9510" refId="ref4212" refString="UTTERIDGE, T. M. A., A. JULIUS &amp; S. SABRAN (2014). Ardisia silamensis, a new ultramafic species from Borneo; studies in Malaysian Myrsinaceae II. Kew Bull. 69: 9510." type="journal article" year="2014">UTTERIDGE et al., 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="261" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="4.[140,790,1050,1298]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
<emphasis box="[177,399,1050,1074]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">Conservation status. –</emphasis>
Populations of 
<taxonomicName box="[565,790,1051,1074]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Benstonea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="serpentinica">
<emphasis box="[565,790,1051,1074]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">Benstonea serpentinica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are only known from 350 to 600 m on Mt. Silam. This patch of forest on ultramafic substrate represents c. 10 km 
<superScript attach="left" box="[709,717,1113,1127]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">2</superScript>
and is part of the Sapagaya FR. Logged forest, palm oil plantations and roads surround nevertheless this mountain, which is under serious human pressure. The new species is therefore preliminary assessed here as “Critically Endangered” [CR B1ab(iii)] following IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" box="[613,751,1274,1298]" firstAuthor="IUCN" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" refId="ref3963" refString="IUCN (2012). IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. 2 nd ed. IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge." type="book" year="2012">IUCN, 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="261" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[140,791,1338,1682]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
<emphasis box="[177,494,1339,1362]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
Notes. – 
<taxonomicName box="[265,494,1339,1362]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Benstonea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="serpentinica">Benstonea serpentinica</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[694,785,1338,1362]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Benstonea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[694,785,1338,1362]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">B. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs by its peduncle (short, 20-25 cm, covered with several prophylls at base vs. long, 40-45 cm, with no prophylls), its smaller drupes (15-20 × 4-5 mm vs. 30 × 8 mm) and style (2-3 vs. 7 mm), style morphology (stout, shortly acuminate, slightly curved proximally vs. spiniform, curved proximally) and fruit colour when ripe (pale green vs. red).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[140,791,1338,1682]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
In their phylogeny of 
<taxonomicName authority=", BUERKI et al. (2016)" authorityName="BUERKI" authorityYear="2016" box="[432,789,1562,1586]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Benstonea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[432,539,1563,1586]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">Benstonea</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="BUERKI" box="[555,789,1562,1586]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="BUERKI" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" pagination="211 - 223" refId="ref3548" refString="BUERKI, S., T. GALLAHER, T. BOOTH, G. BREWER, F. FOREST, J. T. PEREIRA &amp; M. W. CALLMANDER (2016). Biogeography and evolution of the screw-pine genus Benstonea Callm &amp; Buerki (Pandanaceae). Candollea 71: 211 - 223. DOI: http: // dx. doi. org / 10.15553 / c 2016 v 712 a 7" type="journal article" year="2016">BUERKI et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
showed that the new species 
<taxonomicName box="[455,607,1595,1618]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Benstonea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="serpentinica">
<emphasis box="[455,607,1595,1618]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">B. serpentinica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to clade IIIc together with 
<emphasis box="[346,446,1626,1650]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
<taxonomicName box="[346,442,1626,1650]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Benstonea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">B. affinis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which is widespread across the Sunda shelf (including the Philippines).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
